Ground Surveillance Radar â€” Detailed Power-Up to Shutdown Sequence

Below is a practical, equipment-level sequence for a typical ground surveillance radar (GSR) (rotary surveillance / 2D ground surveillance, including surface-search). I assume a radar with antenna drive, transmitter (TWT/solid-state), receiver/processor, IFF/SSR, operator console, cooling, and data link. Times shown are typical ranges â€” adjust to your specific equipment manual.


---

1 â€” Main Power ON

1. Turn MAIN POWER ON (mains/circuit breaker).


2. External utility checks: verify correct phase, voltage within tolerance, and grounding connection.


3. Local power distribution energized (external UPS or generator if present).



What happens: power rails energize; fans begin; control processor starts.


---

2 â€” Power-On Self Test (POST) & Safety Interlocks

1. Control processor runs POST / Built-In Tests (BIT).


2. Confirm:

Power supply voltages within limits.

Cooling fans operational and minimum airflow achieved.

Door/interlock switches and RF kill switch state.

Emergency stop/grounding strap presence.



3. Any critical fault â†’ System locks out and displays alarm.



Operator action: check indicator panel and fault log; clear only after corrective action.


---

3 â€” Controller & Network Initialization

1. Radar Controller / CPU boots firmware and loads configuration (site offsets, antenna limits, PRF sets).


2. Initialize communications:

Console/display unit(s) link.

Network time sync / GPS if present.

Data link to C2 / recorder / remote displays.



3. Health messages streamed to operator console.




---

4 â€” Antenna & Servo System Initialization

1. Power applied to antenna drive servos only after BIT OK.


2. Run servo homing routine (find mechanical zero).


3. Perform limit switch checks and encoder verification.


4. Slow test rotation (manual jog) to confirm bearings, slip rings, and rotor brakes.



Warnings: If vibration/noise detected, stop and inspect.


---

5 â€” RF Subsystem Warm-Up

1. Apply low-voltage to transmitter heaters/filaments (for tube-based TWT/magnetron) or enable SST power stages (for solid-state).


2. Wait warm-up timer (typical: 30 s â€” 5 min depending on transmitter type).


3. During warm-up receiver front-end, LNA bias, and local oscillators stabilize.



Indicator: â€œWARM-UPâ€ or â€œSTANDBYâ€ illuminated.


---

6 â€” Receiver & Signal Processor Self-Calibration

1. Internal loopback tests: inject calibration pulses to receiver chain.


2. Automatic alignment/calibration of:

I/Q balance and DC offset.

Range gate alignment and timebase.

Clutter filters and doppler baseline (if applicable).



3. If radar uses pulse compression, verify matched filter response.



Operator action: review calibration report; accept or re-run if spec out.


---

7 â€” Safety & Mission Prechecks (Operator)

1. Confirm RF exclusion zones and personnel clearances.


2. Verify IFF/SSR and friend/foe interfaces (if fitted).


3. Set mission parameters: scan sectors, range scales, PRF, beam tilt, dwell time, track priors.


4. Input site-specific parameters: antenna height, platform stabilization mode (if mobile), land clutter masks.




---

8 â€” Standby â†’ Transmit Enable

1. Operator moves system from STANDBY â†’ OPERATE (often a guarded switch).


2. Control logic applies high voltage to transmitter (with interlocks verifying antenna direction, waveguide protections, and RF safety door closed).


3. Transmitter keyed and the radar begins emitting pulses at low duty cycle for verification.



Auto checks: monitor transmitter forward/reflected power; arc detectors; HV leakage.


---

9 â€” Antenna Rotation & Initial Scan

1. Antenna accelerates to commanded RPM/scan rate (or slews to programmed sector).


2. First full sweep performed; returns processed echo maps to console.


3. Automatic clutter map building and background subtraction begins (requires several revolutions to stabilize).



Time: initial map/ground-clutter settling often requires 2â€“10 sweeps.


---

10 â€” Detection & Tracking Modes

1. Search Mode: continuous scanning for targets; operator sets sensitivity, threshold.


2. GMTI/MTI (if available): moving target indicator processing engaged â€” tune clutter filter/gate settings.


3. Track-While-Scan (TWS): automatic trackers initialize when detections exceed thresholds; tracks are created, updated, and assigned IDs.


4. Priority Modes: manual/auto cueing to sectors of interest, sector focusing, and high-PRF/low-PRF switching for range/velocity ambiguity handling.



Operator: supervise tracks, validate false alarms, adjust thresholds.


---

11 â€” Data Output & Integration

1. Track and detection data forwarded to C2, plotting systems, recorders via data link (e.g., Ethernet, MIL-STD interface).


2. Optionally enable video/radar-plot recording for post-mission analysis.


3. IFF interrogator (if present) requests/resolves friend or unknown contacts.




---

12 â€” Continuous Health Monitoring

1. Real-time monitoring of thermal, voltage, current, and RF parameters.


2. Predictive alarms (e.g., rising cavity temperature, fault counters increasing).


3. Automatic protective actions:

Reduce duty cycle or power if overheating.

Transmitter trip and revert to STANDBY on critical faults.



4. Logs and S.M.A.R.T-type alerts stored for maintenance.




---

13 â€” Fault Handling / Fault Recovery

1. Non-critical faults: auto-retry or degrade gracefully (e.g., lower power, reduce scan rate).


2. Critical faults: automatic shutdown of transmitter, park antenna, notify operator with fault code and recommended action.


3. Operator performs guided recovery (reset, clear, component swap, call maintenance).




---

14 â€” Standby / Park (Temporary Stop)

1. To pause operations without full shutdown: switch to STANDBY â€” transmitter keyed off, receiver remains active.


2. Antenna brought to park position (if required) or allowed to continue passive rotation.


3. Cooling fans remain active.




---

15 â€” Normal Shutdown

1. Operator commands OPERATE â†’ STANDBY. Wait for HV and RF to discharge â€” confirm transmitter HV is zero.


2. Park antenna and put servos into safe state (lock brakes if needed).


3. Turn MAIN POWER OFF after processors complete safe-shutdown and fans have run for required cooldown (typical: 1â€“5 minutes).


4. Archive logs and record operational notes.



Safety: ensure that all HV is discharged and that any rotating equipment is stopped before maintenance.


---

16 â€” Post-Shutdown Maintenance / Log

1. Inspect for any red/amber warnings logged during session.


2. Schedule preventive tasks: filter changes, bearing lubrication, cooling check, waveguide inspection.


3. Store radar data (mission logs, recorder) to secure storage.




---

Quick Troubleshooting Checklist (Common Issues)

Antenna not rotating: check servo power, encoder feedback, limit switches.

No echoes / low sensitivity: verify receiver LNA bias, front-end attenuators, antenna feed integrity.

High reflected power: inspect waveguide load, antenna alignment, bird/wildlife or obstructions.

Transmitter trips at high temp: reduce duty cycle; check cooling and airflow.

Excess false alarms: adjust clutter map / thresholds / PRF settings.



---

Safety & Site-Specific Notes

Always follow the equipment Manufacturerâ€™s Maintenance Manual (MMM) and local RF safety regulations.

Maintain an RF exclusion zone and visible RF ON indicators while transmitting.

For mobile GSRs, verify stabilization/leveling before enabling transmit.



